hondo717: |CP||AT|We went over the important bidding principles here, but I will review them. In modern bidding, there are many different kinds of raises available, depending on how many trumps you have, and how many points. It is important that you pick the correct one in every auction. In a competitive auction, where partner bids a suit and the next person overcalls, the cue bid as limit raise or better is an excellent bid. Therefore, if you raise without making a cue bid, that denies a limit raise. It is very important that you cue bid when you have a limit raise, otherwise partner will miss game sometimes.|
PG| ***** 124 ***** |


NT|^B@2|CP|8|AT|
hondo717: |CP||AT|The other important point is, once you describe your hand, you can pass if you have no further information to give to partner. On this particular hand, once gale bids 3@D, anna knows everything about gale's hand, gale has 10-12 pts and 4 spades. BTW, I play a cue bid promises 4 trumps, although some people will do it with 3.  The reason I like it to show 4 card support is that a nine card fit is worth about half a trick more than an eight card fit with the same number of points, so partner can bid close games if they know you have a nine card fit. Usually, if partner has a good 14, they should bid game, otherwise not.|
