hondo717: |cp||at|anna played this brilliantly, unfortunately her partner did no bid this so brilliantly. This is quite an interesting hand, actually. The bidding was fine up to 3@D at least.  anna's bidding illustrates an important principle. Once you limit your hand with your first bid, it is much easier to bid more freely, because it is hard to over bid. In this particular case, anna passed originally, denying six points. her pass was correct, particularly with a singleton club.   Therefore, once I bid 2@D, showing a strong hand with longer clubs than diamonds, anna can easily bid 3@D, because I know she doesn't have six points.  |
PG| ***** 147 ***** |


NT|^B@2|cp|8|at|
hondo717: |cp||at|Next, I decided with my hand, since I only had 4 diamonds and anna had less than six points, that the chances of making 5@D were not that good, so I chose to pass. However, 5@D turns out to be a good contract. Obviously, since I can see all 4 hands, I could bid 5@D, but at a real table I think I would pass, so that is why I did so. Looking at the hand again, I think I was a bit conservative, but I figured it was likely we lose 1 club, 1 heart, and 1 diamond. The important principle here is once anna passed the 1@C bid, she could bid 3@D with great confidence.|
