NT|^B@2|cp|8|at|
hondo717: |cp||at|Now let me briefly discuss odd/even discards, even though they did not come up on this hand. Basically, odd/even discards are a defensive signaling system. The first time a defender discards, that is does not follow suit, is when they apply. If the defender discards an odd card, it means the defender likes that suit, and is showing some cards in that suit. If the defender discards an even card, it means he/she does not like that suit. Some people also play an even card is suit preference for the other two suits, but I don't like that. |
PG| ***** 151 ***** |


NT|^B@2|cp|8|at|
hondo717: |cp||at|More often than not, you don't want to encourage in any suit, but if you play an even card is suit preference, you have to encourage some suit. So, if you play odd/even, I suggest you keep it simple -- odd encourages, even discourages. Remember, it is only the first discard-- the first time a defender does not follow suit.|
