hondo717: |cp||at|Now, responses to 2@C.  As most of you know, the modern tendency is to play 2@D waiting. My 2@D bid doesn't mean much. It is almost forced. If I have a good 5 card suit, with two of the top three honors, I can bid that suit instead of 2@D. Otherwise, I must bid 2@D over 2@C. Then, 2@H, 2@S, 3@C, or 3@D bids show good 5+ card suit with 2 of the top 3|
PG| ***** 164 ***** |


NT|^B@2|cp|8|at|
hondo717: |cp||at|Probably the most common method of showing a negative hand by responder is a 2@H artificial response over 2@C. A bid of 2@H over 2@C, shows a hand with no aces or kings. In fact, on the hand I had, I could bid 2@H if I wanted over 2@C. If we played that system, then moe would know that he should stop at 4@H  since I denied any aces or kings. The reason you concentrate on aces and kings, is because they are usually much more important to the 2@C bidder than Qs and Js. If you play 2@H is negative over 2@C, then a 2N bid by responder shows a heart suit.|
PG| ***** 165 ***** |


NT|^B@2|cp|8|at| 
hondo717: |cp||at|Some people don't like to play 2@H showing a negative hand.  They play what is known as "2nd negative."  In this treatment with a bad hand responder  first bids 2@D and then he bids the cheapest minor over a non-NT rebid by the 2@C opener. For example, the auction 2@C-2@D-2@H-3@C, shows responder has a bad hand. It says nothing about clubs  3@C is the cheapest minor in that case. Similarly, 2@C-2@D-3@C-3@D shows a bad hand (again, cheapest minor.) Personally, I prefer the 2@H negative to the cheapest minor "2nd negative." |
